rComments: I did pretty good in the course, but I am kind of a math person. Benj Hellie, however, was a different story. He was quite sarcastic and low-key rude to a few students whose questions he didn't like. A professor should not be like this.

The course Puzzles and Paradoxes is quite easy if you are a natural at logic. However, don't expect Benj Hellie to clearly explain things in class, even if you ask questions and pay attention is class. He is not very proficient at explaining concepts. You have to study on your own.

The material he covers cannot be found anywhere but his textbook because he literally teaches his own theories. I don't think anyone really understood what he was saying most of the time, and as the semester went by, his classes just got emptier and emptier. Please, do not take Puzzles and Paradoxes with him no matter how fun the name may sound.

I had him for philosophy and let's just say your assignments are not what he teaches in the lectures. Lectures will help comprehend the theory however he doesn't help how to put the theory into the assignments. He has a great personality. however as a professor it's not that great. You'll need to do outside research to better comprehend the course.

Just what you would expect from a course called "puzzles and paradoxes"; it's something that will melt your brain and really get you thinking. It's hard content to wrap your head around, and some just get frustrated with it.  As a prof, he's a funny guy,  but sometimes he doesn't realize that he's the smartest in the room and we cant alway keep up.

Judging him from just his huge lectures and concluding he isn't a fantastic professor is what some do and I respect that; however, as a one-on-one teacher of hard to grasp concepts, he is unparalleled. The amount of respect he has for his students is also a real plus. I'm already signed up for more classes with him!
The course, being puzzles and paradoxes, is naturally confusing. However, if you attend his office hours for a 1 on 1 conversation, he does a great job of clearing everything up.
